/-! ## 1. M√∂bius Decomposition Identity

The algebraic core of the M√∂bius decomposition: for any function `f` and positive
integer `n`, the M√∂bius inversion sum `‚àë_{(a,b) ‚àà n.divisorsAntidiagonal} Œº(a)¬∑f(b)`
splits into the main term from `b = 1` and the error sum from `b > 1`.
-/

/-
In the divisors antidiagonal of a positive integer `n`, the only pair `(a, b)` with
`b ‚â§ 1` is `(n, 1)`, since `a * b = n > 0` forces `b ‚â• 1`.

In n.divisorsAntidiagonal, elements (a,b) satisfy a * b = n and n ‚âÝ 0. If ¬¨(1 < b), then b ‚â§ 1. Since a * b = n > 0, we need b > 0, so b ‚â• 1. Combined: b = 1, hence a = n. Conversely (n,1) ‚àà divisorsAntidiagonal since n * 1 = n and n ‚âÝ 0. Use ext to show equality of Finsets, then unfold mem_filter and mem_divisorsAntidiagonal.
-/
lemma divisorsAntidiagonal_filter_snd_le_one {n : ‚Ñï} (hn : 0 < n) :
    n.divisorsAntidiagonal.filter (fun x => ¬¨(1 < x.2)) = {(n, 1)} := by
  ext;
  norm_num +zetaDelta at *;
  constructor;
  ¬∑ rintro ‚ü® ‚ü® h‚ÇÅ, h‚ÇÇ ‚ü©, h‚ÇÉ ‚ü©;
    cases h‚ÇÉ.eq_or_lt <;> aesop;
  ¬∑ aesop

/-
**M√∂bius decomposition (crt_counting_mobius_decomp)**: The M√∂bius inversion sum
over `n.divisorsAntidiagonal` decomposes into the main term `Œº(n) ¬∑ f(1)` plus the
error sum over pairs `(a, b)` with `b > 1` (i.e., proper divisors of `n`).

This formulates the counting function over the CRT lattice as a M√∂bius sum,
isolating the main term and reorganising the error term exactly into the form
`‚àë_{d|q, d>1}`.

Use Finset.sum_filter_add_sum_filter_not to split n.divisorsAntidiagonal into filter(1 < x.2) and filter(¬¨(1 < x.2)). The latter equals {(n,1)} by divisorsAntidiagonal_filter_snd_le_one. Then rearrange with add_comm.
-/
theorem crt_counting_mobius_decomp {n : ‚Ñï} (hn : 0 < n) (f : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ‚Ñù) :
    ‚àë x ‚àà n.divisorsAntidiagonal,
      (‚Üë(ArithmeticFunction.moebius x.1) : ‚Ñù) * f x.2 =
    (‚Üë(ArithmeticFunction.moebius n) : ‚Ñù) * f 1 +
      ‚àë x ‚àà n.divisorsAntidiagonal.filter (fun x => 1 < x.2),
        (‚Üë(ArithmeticFunction.moebius x.1) : ‚Ñù) * f x.2 := by
  have h_split : ‚àë x ‚àà n.divisorsAntidiagonal, (ArithmeticFunction.moebius x.1) * f x.2 = ‚àë x ‚àà n.divisorsAntidiagonal.filter (fun x => ¬¨(1 < x.2)), (ArithmeticFunction.moebius x.1) * f x.2 + ‚àë x ‚àà n.divisorsAntidiagonal.filter (fun x => 1 < x.2), (ArithmeticFunction.moebius x.1) * f x.2 := by
    rw [ Finset.sum_filter, Finset.sum_filter ] ; rw [ ‚Üê Finset.sum_add_distrib ] ; congr ; ext ; split_ifs <;> aesop;
  rw [ h_split, divisorsAntidiagonal_filter_snd_le_one hn ] ; norm_num

/-! ## 2. Divisor Contribution Bound

For a single divisor `d | q`, the contribution to the boundary deviation is bounded
using two ingredients:

1. **Period cancellation** (`deviation_sum_period_zero`): the unweighted deviation
   sum over all residue classes is zero.
2. **Box counting** (`box_card_upper_bound`): the number of lattice points in the
   boundary (incomplete `d`-period) is controlled.

The abstract principle: when `‚àë f = 0` and `|f| ‚â§ M`, the weighted sum `‚àë w ¬∑ f`
is controlled by the total variation of the weights. The total variation of the
multiplicities from their average is exactly the boundary contribution, bounded by
`O(s^{k-2} / d^{k-2})` via `box_card_upper_bound` applied with scaling `s/d`.
-/

/-
**Divisor contribution bound (d_contribution_bound)**: When a function `f`
sums to zero and is pointwise bounded by `M`, any weighted sum `‚àë w(x) ¬∑ f(x)` is
controlled by the total variation of the weights from an arbitrary baseline `c`.

Applied in context: `f(g)` is the deviation `N_k(0::g) - Œº` (sums to zero by
`deviation_sum_period_zero`, bounded by `2|Œ©|` via `individual_deviation_bound`),
and `w(g)` is the multiplicity of residue class `g` in the box. The total variation
`‚àë |w(g) - c|` measures the boundary of incomplete `d`-periods, bounded by
`box_card_upper_bound` with scaling `s/d`.

The constant `M` and the total variation are both `q`-independent, ensuring the
overall bound `O(s^{k-2} / d^{k-2})` is `q`-independent.

Step 1: Show ‚àë w * f = ‚àë (w - c) * f. Since ‚àë f = 0, we have c * ‚àë f = 0, so ‚àë w*f = ‚àë (w-c)*f + c*‚àëf = ‚àë (w-c)*f. Use simp_rw [sub_mul] and Finset.sum_sub_distrib.

Step 2: |‚àë (w-c)*f| ‚â§ ‚àë |w-c|*|f| by triangle inequality (Finset.abs_sum_le_sum_abs). Then ‚àë |w-c|*|f| ‚â§ ‚àë |w-c|*M by pointwise bound hM and abs_nonneg. Finally ‚àë |w-c|*M = (‚àë |w-c|)*M by Finset.sum_mul.
-/
theorem d_contribution_bound {Œπ : Type*} [Fintype Œπ] (f w : Œπ ‚Üí ‚Ñù)
    (hf_sum : ‚àë x, f x = 0) (M : ‚Ñù) (hM : ‚àÄ x, |f x| ‚â§ M)
    (c : ‚Ñù) :
    |‚àë x, w x * f x| ‚â§ (‚àë x, |w x - c|) * M := by
  -- By linearity of summation, we have:
  have h_sum_eq : ‚àë x, w x * f x = ‚àë x, (w x - c) * f x := by
    simp +decide [ sub_mul, Finset.sum_sub_distrib ];
    simp +decide [ ‚Üê Finset.mul_sum _ _ _, hf_sum ];
  exact h_sum_eq.symm ‚ñ∏ le_trans ( Finset.abs_sum_le_sum_abs _ _ ) ( by simpa only [ Finset.sum_mul _ _ _ ] using Finset.sum_le_sum fun i _ => by rw [ abs_mul ] ; exact mul_le_mul_of_nonneg_left ( hM i ) ( abs_nonneg _ ) )

/-! ## 3. Divisor Sum Convergence

The series `‚àë_{d} d^{-(k-2+Œµ)}` converges for `k ‚â• 3` and `Œµ > 0`, since the
exponent `k - 2 + Œµ ‚â• 1 + Œµ > 1`. For `k = 2`, the exponent is `Œµ` alone,
which may be less than 1; this critical case is handled by the paper's analysis
of the exponent `Œª‚ÇÇ = (‚àö17 - 3)/2` and standard bounds on the divisor function.
-/

/-
**Convergence for k ‚â• 3**: The p-series `‚àë d^{-(k-2+Œµ)}` converges when
`k ‚â• 3` and `Œµ > 0`, as the exponent `k - 2 + Œµ ‚â• 1 + Œµ > 1`.

Apply Real.summable_nat_rpow_inv.mpr. Need to show 1 < (k : ‚Ñù) - 2 + Œµ. Since k ‚â• 3 (cast to ‚Ñù), we have (k:‚Ñù) - 2 ‚â• 1, so (k:‚Ñù) - 2 + Œµ ‚â• 1 + Œµ > 1. Use linarith with the cast.
-/
theorem divisor_sum_convergence_k_ge_3 {k : ‚Ñï} (hk : 3 ‚â§ k) (Œµ : ‚Ñù) (hŒµ : 0 < Œµ) :
    Summable (fun n : ‚Ñï => ((n : ‚Ñù) ^ ((k : ‚Ñù) - 2 + Œµ))‚Åª¬π) := by
  exact Real.summable_nat_rpow_inv.mpr ( by linarith [ show ( k : ‚Ñù ) ‚â• 3 by norm_cast ] )

/-
**Convergence for k = 2 (critical exponent)**: For `k = 2`, the divisor sum
convergence requires the exponent `Œ±` to exceed 1. The paper's critical exponent
`Œª‚ÇÇ = (‚àö17 - 3)/2 ‚âà 0.56` combined with the spacing bound `s ‚â§ p^{Œª‚ÇÇ - Œµ}`
ensures an effective exponent `> 1` after accounting for the divisor function bound.

This lemma captures the general summability criterion used in both the `k = 2`
and `k ‚â• 3` regimes.

Directly apply Real.summable_nat_rpow_inv.mpr hŒ±.
-/
theorem divisor_sum_convergence_k_eq_2 (Œ± : ‚Ñù) (hŒ± : 1 < Œ±) :
    Summable (fun n : ‚Ñï => ((n : ‚Ñù) ^ Œ±)‚Åª¬π) := by
  exact Real.summable_nat_rpow_inv.2 hŒ±

/-
**Unified convergence (divisor_sum_convergence)**: The divisor power series
`‚àë d^{-(k-2+Œµ)}` converges whenever the exponent `(k : ‚Ñù) - 2 + Œµ` exceeds 1.
For `k ‚â• 3`, this holds automatically for any `Œµ > 0`.
For `k = 2`, the hypothesis `1 < Œµ` is needed, which follows from the paper's
analysis of the critical exponent `Œª‚ÇÇ` and the well-distribution hypothesis.

Directly apply Real.summable_nat_rpow_inv.mpr hexp.
-/
theorem divisor_sum_convergence (k : ‚Ñï) (_hk : 2 ‚â§ k) (Œµ : ‚Ñù) (_hŒµ : 0 < Œµ)
    (hexp : 1 < (k : ‚Ñù) - 2 + Œµ) :
    Summable (fun n : ‚Ñï => ((n : ‚Ñù) ^ ((k : ‚Ñù) - 2 + Œµ))‚Åª¬π) := by
  exact Real.summable_nat_rpow_inv.2 hexp

end PoissonCRT
